The problem with inaccessable networks is not restricted to the
non-US parts of the Internet. I notice that the Alternet people
advertise that they are connected to the Internet for those of
their customers who are so authorized. How do the domain names
work for those who aren't authorized? 

Another question is: what is the attitude of the owners of the
domain name system? (I presume that the root of the DNS is owned
by the nic or iab or something). Do they mind NS entries pointing
to inaccessable hosts? Such NS entries will cause queries to
always timeout. Is this a fatal error for a mail message or does
MX mail software requeue messages when the DNS query times out?
[I realise that the correct answer is to ensure that every domain
in the inaccessable world has a secondary in the real world: another
job for uunet. How much can one machine do?]

Bob Smart &lt;smart@mel.dit.csiro.au&gt;

P.S. I notice that the pretence that the 3 letter top level domains
are international is fading. A recent poster claimed that .GOV is
restricted to US federal government organizations. I know that .EDU
and .ORG are truly international but the future of that seems
dubious when cern (an international organization) prefers .ch to .org
and the Canadians are deserting .edu for .ca. Some people see the
3 letter top level domains as a sort of cultural imperialism. This
is unfair: it just like the British not puting "UK" on their stamps
-- when you're first you take liberties (and keep them). However I'm
sure it will be better for all concerned if the US makes greater use
of the .US domain. Since all current subdomains of .US are 2 letters
you could easily add 3 letter subdomains for other purposes.

